  "title": {
    "en": "Foods",
    "uz": "Taomlar"
  },
  "icon": "🍲",
  "blurb": "Plov, soups and the colours of the bazaar",
  "article": [
    {
      "heading": "A cuisine built around the dasturxon",
      "body": [
        "Meals gather around the **dasturxon**, the spread of food laid out for guests. At its heart is **palov** (also called *osh*) — rice with carrots, onion and meat, cooked in a great cast-iron *qozon*. Around it come hand-folded **manti** (steamed dumplings), pulled-noodle **lag'mon**, and hearty **sho'rva** soup.",
        "Uzbek hospitality is generous to a fault: expect your plate to be refilled before it is ever empty."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "palov",
          "english": "plov — the national dish"
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "manti yaxshi",
          "english": "the manti is good"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "Colours of the bazaar",
      "body": [
        "The markets overflow with produce. Look for **anor** (pomegranate), **qovun** (melon) — Uzbek melons are legendary — and **tarvuz** (watermelon), piled in fragrant pyramids. Cooking starts from **sabzi** (carrot), **piyoz** (onion) and **kartoshka** (potato), and a touch of **asal** (honey) sweetens the tea."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "qovun shirin",
          "english": "the melon is sweet"
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "bir kilo anor",
          "english": "one kilo of pomegranates"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
